That noted, chip design takes time, and while OpenAI contributed to this de=
sign =E2=80=94 I was told in a briefing that there are customizations down =
to the silicon focused on OpenAI models =E2=80=94 Maia appears to be an imp=
ressive performer that isn=E2=80=99t as suited to large language models (LL=
Ms) as it could be. From Dylan Patel at SemiAnalysis ( https://www.semianal=
ysis.com/p/microsoft-infrastructure-ai-and-cpu ) :

The FLOPS of this chip outright crush Google=E2=80=99s TPUv5 (Viperfish) as=
 well as Amazon=E2=80=99s Trainium/Inferentia2 chips. Surprisingly it=E2=80=
=99s not even that far off from Nvidia=E2=80=99s H100 and AMD=E2=80=99s MI3=
00X in that department. The more relevant spec here is the memory bandwidth=
 at 1.6TB/s. This still crushes Trainium/Inferentia2, but it is less memory=
 bandwidth than even the TPUv5, let alone the H100 and MI300X. Microsoft un=
fortunately underspecced Maia 100 in memory bandwidth.

This is because the chip was designed before the LLM craze happened. As suc=
h Maia is a bit unbalanced in terms of on die memory vs off die memory. Mic=
rosoft put a load of SRAM on the chip, because large amounts of SRAM make s=
ense for some model architectures. Large caches generally help reduce the m=
emory bandwidth that is required, but that doesn=E2=80=99t apply to large l=
anguage models.

Very large LLM=E2=80=99s like GPT-4 need a lot of memory =E2=80=94 more tha=
n you can feasibly put on a single chip =E2=80=94 which means the optimal a=
pproach emphasizes linking multiple chips together; Maia, though, optimized=
 for memory on the chip. I don=E2=80=99t know the particulars of this desig=
n choice, but I can imagine there was a lot of thought given to products li=
ke Azure Arc ( https://azure.microsoft.com/en-us/products/azure-arc ) , whi=
ch lets companies run Azure on the edge; there are machine learning applica=
tions where having one highly capable chip with a lot of memory fits the bi=
ll perfectly, and that may have influenced Maia=E2=80=99s design direction =
when it was first decided on years ago.

I suspect this is why Maia=E2=80=99s initial deployment will be for Microso=
ft=E2=80=99s internal use; Microsoft can direct workloads to Maia for which=
 it is well-suited, without developers having to discern what processor is =
best for what workload (and, at least for now, avoid any public benchmarkin=
g).

